lyrics:

The dark drains its bright seeds,
on the old town of Ypsilanti, MI.

The suburban nocturnal nerve:
the florescent glow of strip malls and car dealerships.

The stillness that winters expose:
the unshifting snow,
that buries the unsalted roads
and grafts in us anew.

comments.comment: YUP is right. Nice one, Wall.

The scene is highway 5. Two brothers embark on what was supposed to be a 2day-long road trip up to Portland. It's early morning- we eat black beans and blast Ewe drumming. Lips, Paul's the affectionately named '79 Light Blue leopard-skinned VW Van was running great. Along the way, we meet an old veteran at a fruit stand. He suggests we make it to Weed and told us of their storied local bar. So we made that our goal and laid heavy on the gas————— but it wouldn't make a difference. Lips made it past Sacramento when her engine gave out. We call AAA. Thank God for AAA- and their policy of 100 free miles of towing. They towed us to Chico. 

While waiting for the auto mechanics diagnosis, Paul befriends a man who we subsequently named 'the awakener'. He gives Paul a book on the spirituality of the Plains Native Americans then tries to convince us to bring him along on our trip. Paul is taken by the awakener and wanted to bring him along. I didn't know about that. A gregarious fellow, he dashed from subject to subject - the state-wide warrant for his arrest, the great spiritual benefits of LSD and DMT, the Conspiracy of the Federal Reserve. Fraternal paranoia ensues and I dash any chance of him fucking the trip up more that it was already fucked. Upon hearing the auto mechanic's sad news that the engine was a lost cause (with two of her cylinders blown), we went to supermarket and got kale which we ate outright. That raw, bitter kale became a metaphor for the whole trip in my mind: unmediated, shitting in the woods, sleeping in Lips, drinking stale gas station coffee, feeling the night cold all night. The machinery of Paul and your narrator was not so different from Lips' sad cylinders. We were two brothers that fit the description of the 1st lines of "Howl". Burning for the 5th level of Maslow's without having attainted the 2nd. 

4 days and 5 AAA tows later, we arrived in Eugene. We're so close- 100 miles away from Portland but no way to get there! The next day, Paul is supposed to start his programming job and I was to catch my flight back to LA. How to make it? We say "hey, the mechanic said that two cylinders were blown, but what about the other two?"". In hopes of a miracle, we start that engine, hit the road, and heroically trek on. —————————- 5 minutes later, I find myself pushing the van in mid-traffic, exhaust fills my lungs as onlookers watch in pity. Desperate to make it to Portland, we leave Lips at the mechanics shop, and parked ourselves on the side of the highway where we constructed a large cardboard sign that said "North". After an hour's fruitless attempt, it was getting dark and we say “let’s breakdown, let’s breakdown and spend way too much on a rental car and just get there”. We get there. Hollow-eyed and in tatters, Paul makes his 1st day of work, I make my flight, and Lips makes her rest in the ancient heavenly connection to the starry dynamo in the machinery of night.

At 45 her ailing mother grew with child
A babe the last hope that the village doctor could prescribe

And slipped from the shtetl right into the grave

Younger than her nieces and in her sisters house
Brothers boxed her ears And ignored her hungry mouth

At thirteen in a New York tenement
The neighbors heard her screams rattle the cement

A delirious child in a hospital room
As The doctors sealed up her immigrant womb

Mini set out to Toronto by train
rejected at the border but she would not be detained

She tore up her ticket and tied up her boots
And continued in the snow putting foot in front of foot

Facing earths meanest jaws before she reached 18
Mini took a chance and worked a leather machine

Mini, free from fancy, with her toughened hands,
Stitched jeweled clasps and Knotted tapered strands

Mini made her fortune and bought the factory
Married a man for love never had a family

Rumi saw into the man's heart.   It was hardened all around like stone, for the merchant was desirous only of his own gain.  "This man's heart is imprisoned in a cage," he thought to himself.  But he agreed to the request, and followed the merchant to his house, which was easy enough to spot from afar since it was the largest and most lavish house in the village.    The merchant led the saint into a large room and there by the window stood a large cage with a lovely plumed bird inside.   True to the merchant's words the bird appeared to possess little vitality as though ill.   Then Rumi began to sing a song and as his soothing words fell upon the ears of the bird, first it began to twitter then at last began to join its voice to the melody of the saint.  Then it let off abruptly and returned to its former state.  
 
   Rumi said to the merchant, "the bird is unhappy because it longs for its freedom."   To which the merchant replied, "I will give the bird anything that it asks for that is within my power, but I cannot grant its freedom.  I am traveling tomorrow for India and will return in forty days.  Ask the bird if there is something that I can bring to it from its homeland."
 
    The saint whispered quietly to the bird who immediately began to flap its wings and burst into a short song.   The merchant was overjoyed to see his favorite possession restored to health.   Rumi then told the merchant that the bird would be fully restored if he were to do the following:  While he was in India, he should visit the nearby forest where birds similar to his own live, and announce to them that one of their sisters is captive within his home.   The merchant was somewhat puzzled with this instruction, but delighted that his bird again greeted him with song, agreed to do as the saint requested.   Rumi then continued on his way.
 
    Several weeks later, when the merchant was in India, and feeling a sudden longing for home and his pet, remembered the saint's instructions and hurried out to the nearby forest.   There, high among the boughs and filling the canopy of trees with their songs were the sister birds.   "O that I had a dozen of these wonderful creatures filling my house with their melodies," he thought, and then in a loud voice he announced, "one of your sisters lives captive in a cage at my home."   No sooner had the merchant spoken these words, then one of the wild birds fell senseless to the ground from one of the boughs of the trees.   For a moment the merchant was shaken by the sight of the bird's sudden death, but then hurried back to his business at the city where he was staying.
 
     When he returned home to his village and entered his house, he was puzzled to see that illness had once again returned to his precious bird.   "What is this?", he exclaimed, "I have followed the saint's instructions."   He then approached the cage and speaking softly to the bird told it of the misfortune that he had encountered in the forest.  "I have sad news for you my friend, for when I told the others of your captivity, one of your sisters fell immediately to the ground dead."  
 
    As soon as these words were spoken, the bird collapsed and fell to the bottom of the cage.  The merchant was aghast.  "What misfortune is this!  Now my bird is dead too!" he exclaimed.  Sorrowfully, he plucked the dead bird from the cage and placed it by the window sill.  At once, the bird revived, flew out the window and perched on a branch far out of reach of the merchant.  "What is the meaning of this?" he cried.   Then, through the power bestowed by the saint, either upon the heart of the man or upon the tongue of the bird, it began to speak and the merchant understood its language.  "You brought not sad news to me, but the way to my freedom," said the bird.  "For my forest sister showed by her action what I had to do in order to free myself.   O man, may your heart be set free to fly from the cage of your greed before it perishes in its captivity."
 
    Then the bird flew away, free at last.

c73030c85c9.info: This track, recorded May 17th 1977 at Rainbow Studios in Hollywood, CA, captures the  band Flight in what was fated to be one of their final sessions before calling it quits later that year.  The group started in 1974 when young rock fan Peter Finderstein met aspiring guitarist Glen Goodrich at Mercer County High School in Markfield, IL.  They soon cajoled two other teens (Norton Miller and Steven Steffers on bass guitar and drums respectively) from nearby towns to join forces for the first incarnation of what would become Flight, then known as Beefalo Virus.  Miller, the band's first bass guitarist, was fired because he did not have a bass guitar.  Steffers suggested his younger brother, Victor, as a replacement.  The others consented.  "I knew how to play 'Wipe Out' by the Ventures, and that was enough - I was in," recalled Victor of his audition.  Budding musicians they were, it was some time before the group found it's footing.  "Stevey had the bass drum pedal on the wrong side for about six months before anyone realized it," said Finderstein, who by this time had begun shortening his surname to "Finders" for the stage.  "My voice was changing and sometimes I couldn't find the right notes.  Talk about microtonality!"  Goodrich meanwhile, was learning guitar solos by Jimi Hendrix and Tony Iommi and progressing very quickly at his instrument.  "I just wanted attention from girls," said Goodrich of those years, "and girls liked good guitar players."  About this time, the name Beefalo Virus was becoming an issue.  The conservative atmosphere of Heartland American was not kind to such aggression.  Recalled Finders, "We just kept getting turned away from clubs.  The name had to go.  I always had a thing for birds and one day I was just looking out my window and saw a stork fly by, and I thought 'Wow man, the gift of flight.'  And that was it.  From then on, that was the name."  Once they had begun gigging, it was only a matter of time before all members of Flight were up to speed musically, learning popular songs of the day like "Hey Bop Sha Lay-Lay" and "It feels Good (So Do it)."  "Kids started turning out from other towns.  We were excited and had the gumption to start trying out our own tunes on stage," said Goodrich.  "I came up with this one riff one day, where you cross your fingers over the A string while hitting the D, and it produced this crazy sound.  We added a bridge, and that was it: our first song."  The song, which the group affectionately named "Dingle" after the Steffer family dog, soon became a local hit.  It was catchy enough to have pop power, and heavy enough to appeal to new kind of listener spawned by the likes of Led Zeppelin and Cream.  "We were into all kinds of stuff," said Steven Steffers, "Everything from the Beatles to the Stones to the heavier stuff like Blue Cheer.  We wanted to combine the lighter stuff with the heavy stuff, and that kinda became our sound."  It was a successful combination indeed.  With Finders providing lyrics, vocal virtuosity and sex appeal, Goodrich suppling catchy/heavy riffs, virtuosic solos, and sex appeal, and the Steffer brothers providing steady rhythmic support, the group was on its way.   Picked up by Elektra records, Flight's first single for a major label, "Salty Peaches" peaked at No. 11 on the pop charts.  The group's eponymous first full-length sold 200,000 copies during it's first month of release in April 1975.  Flight was soon touring the country.  "We were in seventh heaven.  I mean, we were  a bunch of kids from little towns in the fields, and all of a sudden we're being driven around the country, playing loud rock'n'roll, laying chicks and smoking dope.  We couldn't believe it."  The Flight tour bus became notorious as a mobile party, with lines of young rock fans crowding it at every major city along tour routes.  Backstage was a continuation of the good times.  Victor Steffers later said in a Rolling Stone interview, "It was about this time that cocaine became a thing.  We liked it because you could stay up all night drinking and not feel tired.  And it made us play wild at shows."  What started as fun quickly turned into addiction and the group spent most of it's advance from Elektra for their second record, "In the Ides of Time" on cocaine.  "We had to record that super sloppy and fast.  We had a lot of creativity in those days, so it turned out ok.  But looking back I wish we'd known better,"  wrote Finders in his 2001 autobiography, Findering Myself: The life and music of Peter Finders.  In the Ides of Time was released in June of 1976, peaked at No. 20 on the American pop charts, and No. 12 in the UK.  "So of course we were booted off to England," laughs Goodrich, "where they hated our guts for ripping off Zep and Sabbath and all the others."  After a brutal 3 week tour where they were booed onstage, insulted in the press, and shortchanged financially, the group returned home, feathers ruffled. "We weren't used to not being loved," Stevey Steffers later said, "and the drugs weren't helping us to cope."  Egos were flaring up to, as Victor Steffers started demanding a chance to add his name to the writing credits.  "I kept coming up with all these riffs and lyrics while the other guys were laying around.  I'd go up to Petey like, 'Hey man, check this out' and he'd just mumble something about, 'That should be on your solo record.  It's not right for Flight.' So I was started to get really frustrated."  Victor's older brother was having troubles of his own, "My wife Sally was pregnant with our second daughter Mindy. We were worried about money.  So I started channeling my energies into design and fashion.  I started Steff, my clothing brand,  in August of '76 as a way to get things rolling for us financially.  And that was before Jesus came into my life, so I was using pretty hard at the time, too."    Peter Finders, whose lyrical strengths had previosuly been focussed on fun, girls, and rock music, was simultaneously experiencing a newfound sense of political awareness.  "I read this article about India, and I was like, 'Fuck, man!'  So from then on I vowed to be political in my music.  We have a duty to spread the word about these kinds of things.  I tried to get the others in on it, but that's just not where their heads were at.  Trying to record our third album was like herding cats, both musically and psychologically, and physically.  Goody would be off noodling, I'd be scrawling down something about Mao in between swigs of SoCo, Stevey'd be on the phone talking to an advertising agency, and fucking Victor would be sitting in the recording booth, high as hell, refusing to play until someone admitted he was a great songwriter."  And that brings us to "Ain't Built For You."  A scathing criticism of harsh immigration policies penned by Finders, with a blusey bounce added by Goodrich, the tune never reached completion.  Flight broke up just a few months after these initial tracks were played down.  Stevey Steffers was not available to add drums that day, as he was on a flight to Japan to meet with investors.  Victor had left the studio in a huff, leaving Goodrich and Finders alone to write.  "It was kind of nice," said Goodrich, "like the old days.  We just worked on the song a little, and at one point we looked at each other, and we were like 'Well, I guess this is it.'  We had done what we wanted to do and it wasn't working anymore.  After laying down the initial tracks we just said, 'No, let it be,' we were kinda trying to be Zen about it, ya know?" "Ain't Built For You" is included as a bonus track in Flight's two disc anthology, "Salty Peaches:  The Epic Flight of Flight 1974-1977" released on compact disc by Rhino Records in 1997.

ee84813092d.info: this song is dedicated to the lovely nuralu who was pulling out of her driveway to rescue my sorry self right before one of the many good Samaritans in this story got my tire on the road to salvation.  the events recounted here are mostly true, though i've combined 5 car guys into one guy. i did learn to change a tire today, and I did not do the guy who taught me how to change a tire justice in this song, because he was above and beyond awesome and laughed at my jokes.  and i left out a really wonderful woman security guard and a random but oddball dude who was lounging on the trunk of his station wagon watching the whole thing and looking up tire repair shops for me on yelp. and at one point, the four of us were gathered around my tire and it was a sentimental moment for me, and maybe for them if they are at all sentimental. whatever. so this song barely says what i wanted to, but i have got to go to bed, because my head hurts so bad and i feel like a crazy person! night y'all xoxoxox p.s. also, please feel free to skip this one bc its too long!!  also, there was this one part where this old man was arguing with the tire patching guy for like 20 minutes trying to get him to drive to his house and patch his tire in his driveway.  and the tire guy refused bc he was tired and wanted to go home and they had the same argument 10 times! and the old dude kept leaving and then returning and they would have the same argument again. and the tire patcher guy said he'd do it for 30 dollars.
